# Product Requirements Document

## Overview

Describe the product or feature at a high level. What is it, who is it for, and why does it matter? Keep this to 2-3 sentences that anyone in the organization can understand.

::callout[kind="info", title="How to use this template"]{
Replace the placeholder text in each section with your own content. Sections marked *{optional} can be removed if they don't apply. The structure is a starting point; adapt it to your team's needs.
}

## Problem Statement

What specific problem does this solve? Describe the current state, the pain it causes, and who experiences it. Ground this in evidence: support tickets, user research, metrics, or direct observation.

## Goals

- Primary goal with a measurable outcome
- Secondary goal tied to a user or business metric
- Tertiary goal that supports the primary

## Non-Goals

- Explicitly out of scope item (and +{why} it's out of scope)
- Another boundary to prevent scope creep

## User Stories

::table[header=true, align=["left", "left", "left"]]{
Persona | Story | Priority
Power user | As a power user, I want to perform bulk actions so I can save time on repetitive tasks | P0
New user | As a new user, I want a guided setup flow so I can reach value quickly | P1
Admin | As an admin, I want audit logs so I can track changes for compliance | P2
}

## Requirements

### Functional Requirements

::anchor[id="req-core"]
1. +{Core workflow} -- Describe the primary user-facing behavior
2. +{Data handling} -- What data is created, read, updated, or deleted
3. +{Integration} -- How this connects to existing systems or APIs
4. +{Error states} -- What happens when things go wrong

### Non-Functional Requirements

1. +{Performance} -- Page loads under 200ms at p95; API responses under 100ms
2. +{Accessibility} -- WCAG 2.1 AA compliance
3. +{Security} -- Authentication, authorization, and data-at-rest encryption
4. +{Reliability} -- 99.9% uptime target with graceful degradation

See ::ref[target="req-core"] for the core functional requirements these support.

## Technical Approach

High-level architecture or implementation strategy. This is not a design doc; keep it to the key decisions that constrain implementation.

::source[language="python"]{
# Example: pseudocode for the core workflow
def process_request(request):
    validated = validate(request)
    result = transform(validated)
    return persist(result)
}

::callout[kind="warning", title="Constraint"]{
This must run within the existing infrastructure budget. No new managed services without VP approval.
}

## Success Metrics

::table[header=true, align=["left", "right", "right"]]{
Metric | Baseline | Target
Task completion rate | 62% | 85%
Time to first value | 12 min | 3 min
Support tickets (weekly) | 40 | 15
}

## Milestones

1. +{Week 1-2} -- Discovery and design; finalize requirements with stakeholders
2. +{Week 3-5} -- Core implementation; functional requirements 1-3
3. +{Week 6} -- Integration testing and security review
4. +{Week 7} -- Beta release to internal users
5. +{Week 8} -- GA release with monitoring and rollback plan

## Risks and Mitigations

::callout[kind="warning", title="Key risks"]{
Identify what could go wrong and how you'll handle it.
}

- +{Technical risk} -- Third-party API rate limits may bottleneck the sync pipeline. *{Mitigation -- implement exponential backoff and a local cache.}
- +{Adoption risk} -- Users may resist changing their existing workflow. *{Mitigation -- run a pilot with 3 teams before full rollout.}
- +{Timeline risk} -- Design review may surface new requirements. *{Mitigation -- timebox discovery to 2 weeks; defer net-new scope to v2.}

## Open Questions

- Who owns the rollout communication plan?
- Do we need a data migration for existing users, or is this net-new only?
- What is the fallback if the third-party API deprecates v2 before we ship?

